Unexplained deaths, elephants - India (Assam) 20010815.1926
[1
Date: Thu 16 Aug 2001 11:03 AM
From: Dr. Rathin Barman <rathinbarman@satyam.net.in>
Source: The Assam Tribune; Natural History of South Asia - General [edited
<nathistory-india@lists.Princeton.EDU>
Via: Michael Woodford (Portugal) <Dinton@aol.com>

NAMERI, Aug 14: At least 7 wild elephants, including 2 calves, were found
dead near Bhorali river inside the Nameri national park in Assam, while 13
other tamed tuskers of the State Forest Department are suffering from
various diseases and have been undergoing treatment at the veterinary
hospital at Chariduar in Sonitpur district for the last 3 days.
Mahendra Saikia of the national park said that at least 7 wild elephants,
including 2 infant tuskers (about 4 years of age), were found dead without
any injury mark near Mahmora camp inside the national park at the bank of
river Bhorali, a tributary of river Brahmaputra, in mysterious
circumstances during the last 72 hours. [In addition the bodies of 2 male
tuskers were found at Pakhoi under Khari forest beat office of the national
park. The Sonitpur district veterinary department suspects that the
unnatural deaths of the wild tuskers might be due to Anthrax, which spreads
in an epidemic form in the nearby forests of Arunchal Pradesh.
--
