Date: 17 Aug 2001
From: Michael Woodford <Dinton@aol.com> [edited

[Regarding the other portions of this posting, I recommend: I.W.Caple,
M.R.Jainudeen, T.D.Buick and C.Y. Song (1978) Some clinico-pathologic
findings in elephants (_Elephas maximus_) infected with _Fasciola
jacksoni_. Journal of Wildlife Diseases Vol: 14, January 1978, Pp. 110-115
--
Michael Woodford
Portugal
<Dinton@aol.com>
[The normal liver fluke species for Asian elephants is _Fasciola jacksoni_.
The species involved here is not clear, though there is a suggestion it is
_F. hepatica_. Wildlife/human interactions on the borders of national parks
are common worldwide and a constant threat to both. Elephants can reduce
crops to nothing overnight. Thanks to Michael for forwarding the
information. - Mod.MHJ
